enia, Croatia, Czechia, and Slovakia, where it is more often spelled in the Slavicized form <b>Fric</b> (see below).","Americanized or Germanized form of Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, and Croatian <b>Fric</b>: from the personal name <i>Fric</i>, a pet form, of German origin (see above), of Old Czech and Slovak <i>Fridrich</i>, Slovenian <i>Friderik</i>, Croatian <i>Fridrik</i>, equivalents of German   Friedrich  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fretz","meanings":["German: variant of   Fritz  ."]},{"name":"Friedrich","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Hans, Ernst, Ewald, Franz, Gerhard, Heiner, Heinz, Helmuth, Klaus, Reinhard.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>frid</i>, <i>fred</i> ‘peace’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’. The name was borne by a 9th-century Christian saint, bishop of Utrecht, and was a hereditary name among the Hohenstaufen ruling family; hence its popularity in central Europe."]},{"name":"Fritzen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Claus.","German and Danish: patronymic or pet form of   Fritz   (see   Friedrich  )."]},{"name":"Fritzler","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Ulrich, Gerhart.","German: from <b>Fritzel</b>, an enlarged form of   Fritz  ."]},{"name":"Fritze","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Erna, Gunther, Hans, Kurt, Otto.","German: variant of   Fritz  ."]},{"name":"Fritzinger","meanings":["German: patronymic from   Fritz  ."]},{"name":"Fritts","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Fritz  ."]}]},{"name":"Matheus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alfredo, Manuel, Gustavo, Rafael, Alejandro, Arnoldo, Eduardo, Elva, Ernesto, Genoveva, Gerardo, Germano.","German and Flemish: from the personal name <i>Matheus</i> (see   Matthew  ). Compare   Mattice  .","Portuguese: variant of   Mateus  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."]},{"name":"Mattice","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Matheus   or perhaps of some similar (like-sounding) cognate, e.g.   Mathes  ,   Mathis   or   Mattis  .","History: The first American bearer of the surname <i>Mattice</i> was Hendrick Mattice, born in Germany, who arrived in NY in 1710. His father's surname was reportedly <i>Matheus</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matheus Fritz was born about 1636, in Germany. He had at least 1 son with Unknown."},"et":{"abt 1636–":"umbes 1636–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1657–1739":"1657–1739","1636–Male":"1636–Surnud","1657":"1657","abt 1636":"umbes 1636","24 July 1657":"24. juuli 1657","1739":"1739","1636":"1636","Hangendeinbach, Wuerttemberg, Germany":"Hangendeinbach, Großdeinbach, Welzheim, Württemberg, Saksamaa","Germany":"Saksamaa"},"fi":{"abt 1636–":"noin 1636–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1657–1739":"1657–1739","1636–Male":"1636–Kuollut","1657":"1657","abt 1636":"noin 1636","24 July 1657":"24. heinäkuuta 1657","1739":"1739","1636":"1636","Hangendeinbach, Wuerttemberg, Germany":"Hangendeinbach, Großdeinbach, Welzheim, Württemberg, Saksa","Germany":"Saksa"},"fr":{"abt 1636–":"environ 1636–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1657–1739":"1657–1739","1636–Male":"1636–Décédé","1657":"1657","abt 1636"